data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with `Thread.Abort` + a `ThreadAbortException`/`ResetAbort` catch block. Here's the full migration:

## Pattern Analysis

| .NET Framework API | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code

**Option 1 — Drop-in replacement** (same signature, work can't be cancelled cooperatively):

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws TimeoutException if timeout expires (.NET 6+)
            return task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

**Option 2 — Recommended** (cooperative cancellation, work actually stops):

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

Callers would change from:

```csharp
// Before
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveResult(), timeout);

// After (Option 2) — pass the token through
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();   // check at safe points
    return ComputeExpensiveResult(ct);
}, timeout);
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Option 1 doesn't stop the work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the timed-out `Task.Run` keeps running in the background. The caller returns, but the work is fire-and-forget. Only use this when the work is side-effect-free. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout allocates a timer. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` gaps** | Cancellation is cooperative — if the work has long-running stretches between checks, the timeout won't be respected promptly. Add checkpoints inside loops and between expensive operations. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads. |

**Option 2 is strongly recommended** — it's the only way to actually stop the work, matching the original `Thread.Abort` intent.
